Phase 1: The Core Mindset ("Crush Your Ego")

Before you type a single prompt, you need the right operating system in your head.



Use AI to learn, not to execute: The goal is building your own mental models, not just getting working output.



Read everything: Never copy-paste blindly. If the AI generates code or a mathematical proof, read through every single line.



Keep a constant feedback loop: Keep a tab open alongside your IDE or notebook. Constantly throw your work in and ask: "Is this good? Are there bugs? What can I do better?"



Phase 2: Top-Down Foundation (The "Aha" Moment)

Start broad. Get the absolute clearest, simplest picture of the concept before diving into the weeds.



Actionable Prompts:



"What are the most fundamental concepts of [topic]? Show it to me in a way I really need to understand."



"Explain this concept to me like I'm 12. Go into detail, but make the core idea obvious."



"What is the intuition behind this algorithm? Why does it work? Draw me an ASCII graph or visual representation to explain it."



(If studying math/physics): "What is the absolute core math intuition behind Laplace equations? Break it down visually."



Phase 3: The Build-and-Debug Loop

This is where you get your hands dirty. Build something, break it, and use the AI to understand why it broke.



Step-by-Step Workflow:



Bounce Ideas: Tell the LLM what you want to make (e.g., a specific FastAPI endpoint or a React component) and ask for an outline.



Write and Debug: Try writing the code. When it fails, paste it into the LLM.



Explain the Parts: Once the code works, don't move on. Ask the LLM: "Explain what this specific block of code does and why we needed it to solve the bug."



Actionable Prompts:



"Be extremely direct and concrete. Show me all the intermediate states and the shapes of the code you produce so I intuitively understand why this happens."



"If you're unsure, show me options. What have others tried? Why does this work while something else didn't? Provide external resources."



Phase 4: Recursive Gap Filling

As you learn, you will realize what you don't know. Chase those gaps relentlessly.



Actionable Prompts (The Follow-Up Engine):



"What does this specific line mean?"



"How does it actually do the thing under the hood?"



"Why did we choose this method over another?"



Phase 5: Validation and Testing

Do not trust that you know it just because it made sense when you read it. Prove it.



Actionable Prompts:



The Reverse Pitch: "Here is my understanding of this topic: [Write your explanation]. Is it correct? Point out any flaws in my logic."



The Stress Test: "Give me a quiz on this. Make it challenging."



The Meta-Analysis: "Look at the questions I just answered. Tell me the fundamental concept that all these questions share in common."



Phase 6: Refinement and Best Practices

Once you understand the mechanics, elevate your standard of work to an expert level.



Actionable Prompts:



"Here is my entire codebase. Give me 10 concrete ideas on what I can do to improve this."



"Refer me to papers or resources to read that expand on this."



"Give me a list of things [Specific Paper/Industry Standard] did differently compared to what I just did. Be extremely concrete about the exact differences."



"What are the industry best practices for doing this?" 

"could yousummarize this in a way that to highlight what is crucial to know and what i need to get out of it to understand it deeply without wasting a lot of time on fluff"
